    Detailed Examination with Code Usage                                        
                                                                                
    We'll inspect the critical loop mentioned in storage.c:                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     175 for (i = 0; i < v_count; i++) {                                        
     176     a_names[i] = ...                                                   
     177     arrays[i] = ...                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Here, v_count exceeds a_count, leading to out-of-bounds access on a_names   
    and arrays.                                                                 
                                                                                
    Proposed Fixes                                                              
                                                                                
    Root Cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    File: storage.c:176                                                         
                                                                                
    Explanation: The loop for initializing a_names and arrays uses v_count      
    (variable count) instead of a_count (array count) as the upper bound. When  
    v_count is greater than a_count, memory is accessed beyond the allocated    
    buffer space, leading to heap corruption and the subsequent crash.          
                                                                                
    Local Fix                                                                   
                                                                                
    Replace the loop control with the correct upper bound:                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     - for (i = 0; i < v_count; i++) {                                          
     + for (i = 0; i < a_count; i++) {                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This simple change ensures the loop does not write beyond allocated memory  
    for a_names and arrays.                                                     
                                                                                
    Global Fix                                                                  
                                                                                
    To prevent similar bugs in the future, consider these program-wide          
    practices:                                                                  
                                                                                
     • Bounded Array Types: Utilize data structures that encapsulate size and   
       bounds checking, automatically adjusting sizes or throwing errors when   
       limits are exceeded.                                                     
     • Abstract Data Handling: Introduce functions for buffer management that   
       inherently handle memory bounds, instead of adjusting pointers directly  
       in various locations.                                                    
     • Auditing and Code Review: Regularly audit external inputs and indexing   
       logic to ensure buffer sizes are correctly managed, especially when      
       dynamic memory allocation is involved.                                   
                                                                                
    With these improvements, the software is made more resilient to memory      
    faults and undefined behavior.                                              
                                                                                
